        "message": "Even well-intentioned advice can come across as victim-blaming. When you suggest someone could have prevented harassment by acting differently, you're implying they're responsible for others' harmful actions.\n\n- Focus on the wrongness of the harassment, not what your child could have done differently\n- Validate their feelings and experiences\n- Place responsibility on the perpetrators\n- Emphasize that no one deserves harassment, regardless of their identity or how they express themselves\n- Offer unconditional support without judgment",
